19 1 "gcd(14^6,15^20);" "6#-%$gcdG6$*$\"#9\"\"'*$\"#:\"#?" }}}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT 261 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 97 " Two integers ar
e \"relatively prime\" if the only positive integer that divides both \+
of them is 1." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 81 "5.  List all the pairs of integers from 100 to 110 that a
re relatively prime.   (" }{TEXT 256 109 "Here you might want to look \+
at the MAPLE Programming Supplement to learn how to do \"for\" and \"i
f\" programs.) " }{TEXT 262 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "     \+
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 89 " An integer is called \"prime\" if it
s only (positive integer) divisors are 1 and itself.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 82 " The MAPLE command \"isprime\" determines whether or
 not a given integer is prime.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "6.  Use isprime it to see if the followi
ng numbers are prime:  29,  35,  1537,  your ss#,   10!+1,  329891. " 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 46 "7.  List the prime numbers between 1 an
d 100. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
134 " The FUNDAMENTAL THEOREM OF ARITHMETIC states that every integer \+
can be factored in a unique way into a product of powers of primes.  \+
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 99 "8.  Use paper and pencil to factor th
e following into their prime decompositions:  10! ,  340704.  " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 263 8 "Answers:
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 54 "The M
APLE command \"ifactor\" does this automatically.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 106 "9.  Use ifactor to verify your results from above.  No
w factor the following numbers:  10!+1 ,  your ss#. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 2 "  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 "Execute the following
 command sequence:" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 49 "274428
0=ifactor(2744280);\n267300=ifactor(267300);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 
0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 39 "2744280*267300=ifactor(2744280*267300);" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 49 "gcd(2744280,267300)=ifactor(
gcd(2744280,267300));" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 49 "lc
m(2744280,267300)=ifactor(lcm(2744280,267300));" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 89 "lcm(2744280,267300)*gcd(2744280,267300)=ifacto
r(lcm(2744280,267300)*gcd(2744280,267300));" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 124 " 10.  Using the FUNDAMENTAL TH
EOREM OF ARITHMETIC, provide a written argument to verify the formula \+
gcd(m,n)lcm(m,n) = mn.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT 264 9 "Argument:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 125 "Demonstrate your argument with two suffi
ciently interesting integers (different from above) and the ifactor co
mmand in MAPLE." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 95 "     For two integers m & n  with  n > or = m we say the \+
\"remainder of n divided by m\" is r if " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
58 "n = qm + r, for integers q >0 & r with 0 < or = r <  m.   " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 159 "11.  With paper and pencil compute the f
ollowing remainders and include your answers:  24 divided by 5,  156 d
ivided by 7,  32 divided by 2,  57 divided by 4. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 265 8 "Answers:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "    In MAPLE this rema
inder is denoted by \"n mod m.\" Verify the above answers with MAPLE. \+
 " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 " 12.
